Miscellaneous notes laid in at end. The exhibition label from the 2012-2013 Chang Octagon exhibition "Collecting Oriental Books for the Columbia University Libraries, 1886-1936" was written by Dagmar A. Riedel.

msContents.summary: Parts 325-333 of the history of the city of Damascus by Ibn ʻAsākir, contains parts of the sections on people with the name ʻUthmān; includes several readers' notes and transmission notes. The leaves have been silked and remounted onto pages measuring 267 x 178 mm.

supportDesc.extent: iv, 202, iv leaves : 235 x 160 (195 x 127 ) mm, bound to 277 x 195 mm

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in naskh in black ink; mostly unpointed.

binding.p: Bound in modern cardboard half covers with marbled paper sides, red leather spine and corners; same marbled paper pastedowns.

origin.p: The item is undated, though transmission notes place the copy in the 12th century; the first transmission note says the copy was heard read by the author on 21 Rabīʻ al-Awwal in the Mosque of Damascus in 536 AH (31 October 1141 CE) (f. 20r).

history.provenance: Purchased in Cairo by Richard Gottheil through the Alexander I. Cotheal fund in 1896 (note in pencil laid in and library bookplate inside front cover).
